      <div class="wrapper">
            <a id="main-content"></a>
                                                


<div class="ds-1col node node-blog view-mode-full view-mode-full clearfix ">

  
  <div class="field field-name-title field-type-ds field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="dc:title"><h2>Trump Repeats False Crime Claims in El Paso</h2></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-bcj-summary field-type-ds field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>The president claims "walls work." But the facts say otherwise.</p>
</div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-real-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><a href="/expert/brennan-center-justice">Brennan Center for Justice</a></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-date field-type-datetime field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><span class="date-display-single" property="dc:date" datatype="xsd:dateTime" content="2019-02-12T08:45:00-05:00">February 12, 2019</span></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-content-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.brennancenter.org/sites/default/files/styles/individual_node_page/public/blog/GettyImages-1129036314.png?itok=qWVpTj9O" width="635" height="335" alt="" /></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-addthis field-type-ds field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style">
<a class="addthis_button_facebook"><img src="/sites/all/themes/bcj-zen/img/icn-share-facebook.png" /></a>
<a class="addthis_button_twitter" addthis:title="Trump Repeats False Crime Claims in El Paso @brennancenter" ><img src="/sites/all/themes/bcj-zen/img/icn-share-twitter.png" /></a>
<a class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share"><img src="/sites/all/themes/bcj-zen/img/icn-share-google.png" /></a>
<a class="addthis_button_email"><img src="/sites/all/themes/bcj-zen/img/icn-share-email.png" /></a>
<a href="/print/21280" title="Print" class="button_print at300b"><img src="/sites/all/themes/bcj-zen/img/icn-print.png"></a>
</div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>At a &ldquo;Finish the Wall&rdquo; rally in El Paso, Texas on Monday, President Trump yet again&nbsp;<a href="https://apnews.com/919a8cd4dfdb4ddebd109204b5d45d5f">repeated</a>&nbsp;his refrain: &ldquo;Walls work.&rdquo; He has attempted to build a case for a border wall around mostly false narratives about crime and undocumented immigrants.</p>
<p>There was concern that Trump would use some of that fear mongering as pretext to declare a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.brennancenter.org/blog/trump-destroying-his-own-case-national-emergency">national emergency</a>&nbsp;if Congress didn&rsquo;t provide funding for a border barrier, though negotiators may be on track to defuse that threat after reaching a tentative funding deal this week.</p>
<p>Still, Trump&rsquo;s rhetoric on crime and immigration is far from the truth. As the Associated Press&nbsp;<a href="https://apnews.com/919a8cd4dfdb4ddebd109204b5d45d5f">reports</a>:</p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px;">&ldquo;You know where [a wall] made a difference is right here in El Paso,&rdquo; he said Monday, adding: &ldquo;They&rsquo;re full of crap when they claim it hasn&rsquo;t made a big difference.&rdquo;</p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px;">But that&rsquo;s not true.</p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px;">El Paso had a murder rate of less than half the national average in 2005, a year before the most recent expansion of its border fence. That&rsquo;s despite being just across the border from Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, a city plagued by drug violence. The FBI&rsquo;s Uniform Crime Report shows that El Paso&rsquo;s annual number of reported violent crimes dropped from nearly 5,000 in 1995 to around 2,700 in 2016. But that corresponded with similar declines in violent crime nationwide and included periods when the city&rsquo;s crime rates increased year over year, despite new fencing and walls.</p>
<p>The Brennan Center&rsquo;s ongoing&nbsp;<a href="https://www.brennancenter.org/publication/crime-trends1990-2016">research</a>&nbsp;into crime data in the nation&rsquo;s largest cities backs this up. Violent crime in the country&rsquo;s major metropolitan areas, including El Paso, has dropped precipitously in the last quarter century.</p>
<p>(Image: Joe Raedle/Getty)</p>
</div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-issues field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><a href="/issues/crime-rates-america" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype="">Crime Rates in America</a></div></div></div></div>    </div><!-- wrapper -->
    </div><!-- /#content -->

    
